# Views, Helpers, and Styles

## ERB

- Plain ERB templates under `app/views/<module>/`. No ViewComponent.
- Keep view files small (~140 lines is the soft cap). Extract partials when they grow.
- Move ruby logic into helpers (`app/helpers/<module>/`), decorators (`app/decorators/<module>/`), or presenters (`app/presenters/<module>/`) — not inline.

## Forms and buttons

- Use the existing form helpers and partials in `app/views/<module>/` — don't introduce a new form-styling system.
- Style is SASS (under `app/assets/stylesheets/`) on top of PureCSS. Don't add Tailwind classes; they are not compiled.
- For dynamic interactions, mount a Vue component on the form via `data-` attributes (see `.agents/rules/javascript.mdc`).

## Pagination

- Pagination is provided by Kaminari. Use the standard helpers (`paginate @collection`, `link_to_prev_page`, `link_to_next_page`) and theme via partials.

## Internationalization

- All copy goes through `t(".key")` lookups so locales stay consistent. See `.agents/rules/i18n.mdc`.

## Turbolinks

- The app uses Turbolinks 5. Avoid full-page-reload assumptions. Use `data-turbolinks="false"` on links that must do a hard navigation, and listen for `turbolinks:load` for one-off JS init.

## Helpers

- Module-specific helpers belong under `app/helpers/<module>/`. Use them for view logic that doesn't belong in a model or decorator.
- Resist the urge to create catch-all helpers. If a helper is only used by one view, it probably belongs as a partial-local variable instead.

## Existing JS controllers

- Before adding new front-end code, search `app/javascript/<module>/` for an existing component or module that does what you need. The codebase has long-lived utilities for toggling, modals, dropdowns, charts, maps, etc.
